"&#xa0;\nThe importance of the Select Committee Process &amp; The Wright Reforms“Any member of a select committee whose cumulative attendance during a Session is below 60% should be automatically discharged at the end of that Session”\n \n&#xa0;\nAttendance generally above 60%&#xa0;Legitimate AbsenceRecommended Penalty System as a form of incentive to attendMPs enter Parliament to make a difference or to scrutinise the government; if they are prevented from doing this then they will look to eradicate any behaviour that leads to this; this will surely mean more MPs feeling incentivised to either attend all possible select committee meetings or contributing via post-meeting reports in their absence.\n&#xa0;\nConcluding Remarks&#xa0;\n20 December 2013\n&#xa0;\n Select Committee – Core Tasks, p.4\n&#xa0;\n Kelly, R. Effectiveness of Select Committee – p.4 \n&#xa0;\n Parliament Website. (2012) ‘\nMichael Gove answers #\nAskGove\n twitter questions during Education Committee evidence session’, \nEducation Select Committee News,\n \nhttp://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/education-committee/news/secretary-of-state-ev-session/\n&#xa0;\n Allen et al. (2013) ‘Revisiting Rebuilding the House: the impact of the Wright reforms’,   \nPolitical and Constitutional Reform Committee\n, London: The Stationary Office Limited\n \nhttp://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmselect/cmpolcon/82/82.pdf\n,\n p.1\n&#xa0;\n Wright et al. (2009) ‘Re-building the House’, \nHouse of Commons Reform Committee, \nLondon: The Stationary Office Limited \nhttp://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200809/cmselect/cmrefhoc/1117/1117.pdf\n (Accessed 2nd December 2013), Ev.4\n&#xa0;\nBeith\n et al. (2012) ‘Select committee effectiveness, resources and powers: Volume I’, \nLiaison Committee\n, London: The Stationary Office Limited \nhttp://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmselect/cmliaisn/697/697.pdf\n [accessed 5\nth\n December 2013],\n p.25\n&#xa0;\n